title: What Even Was That
report:
Welcome back to the Jart Report after a week nine composed of extremely weird fantasy performances and low scores across the board. While The Family continues to struggle with their second straight 11th PF performance, we remain committed to bringing you the best analysis in the business.

Week Nine Recap

To start, we are going to be looking back at how week nine unfolded versus the predictions that the Jart Team put together. The team strives to learn from previous weeks to make the most informed predictions, and as we have moved into the middle of the season we hope to improve in accuracy considerably. This week was potentially the weirdest week in fantasy history though. We will go matchup by matchup and look at what we learned as the season begins to take shape.

Prediction: Team ACL Tear by 13.4

Reality: Team Ross by 7.14

Jart’s Mailbag

Can we get manager rankings out of Jart? (Based on transactions, starting the right guys, etc.)

  1. NN. While mostly this has been achieved through abusing Nooni, it’s paid off. The roster looks nice top to bottom, and although he hasn’t been perfect, he claims our top spot.
  2. CJ. The lack of acquisitions hinders some, but sometimes no acquisitions is a good thing. CJ has weathered the storm of Chubb and Dmont injuries with solid depth, and is sitting nicely right now. Wentz proved a great Rodgers fill-in as well.
  3. Jason. He can’t make his guys play well, and his bench depth was certainly lacking this year, but he acquired what was the most talented starting lineup in league history.
  4. Aross. Propelled primarily through his draft night trade, Aross continues to just be solid. Nothing too wild, but he works in calm fashion and gets what he needs. Not the flashiest, but effective.
  5. Folbe. When I think of Folbe, I think of Tim Patrick. And how he was bad on Folbe’s team and great off of it. But besides that, been pretty solid.
  6. Dmichs. Really the only notable move here is buying Damien Harris from Nooni, but that’s paid off nicely. If it ain’t broke! The draft night trade with Alex is what hinders him some.
  7. Bank. Has a knack for WR2s. AJ Dillon a nice pickup, but picking up and starting Jordan Love is worthy of being 12th on this list.
  8. Jart. I know many of you think I should be last on this list given my lineup efficiency standings, but a lot of that has come from waiver acquisitions that have proven highly effective. Cordarelle Patterson was a number of those weeks, and he turned into Davante Adams. And this last week, Aiyuk outscored Tyreek Hill by double digits. Never would have played Aiyuk over Hill, Adams, or Chase, but my lineup efficiency was impacted by ~12% this week for it.
  9. JL. Stick with me here. But he had indisputably the best team early on. But I think he just got too comfortable with that, realized his lead was slipping, and panicked some. These rankings are certainly fluid, but I think JL’s team has gotten worse over the season.
  10. MW. He has had some occasional nice adds, most notably Devontae Booker and Pat Friermuth, but not much else has happened. The MW approach seems to be to trust the draft and add a solid RB, but the WR depth on this team is atrocious.
  11. Brad. $99 for Elijah Mitchell really hasn’t been too bad, but this team is struggling and has poor lineup efficiency. Outside of Elijah the waiver moves haven’t stuck out, but if Cordarelle continues to outperform Davante Adams he’ll get a bump.
  12. Nooni. We all know why (plus $94 on Damien Williams).

Is this the most competitive season in league history?

I think to date, this has been the most competitive season. Everyone is really in the thick of it and no one has separated themselves yet in terms of having the record and the team to back it up. However, in the long term I do not think this season will end up that way. The formation of some elite rosters cannot be ignored, and at some point one would expect those rosters to perform. Unlike the past couple of years, this seems like a year where a team with an elite roster that has not quite gotten the wins sneaks into the playoffs and then dominates the teams with byes. So, if that sounds competitive to you, then yes! But if that sounds like hidden separation because of injuries and poor performances that have impacted records and scores, then no.

How far could nooni have gone had he not traded away all of his great players?

While the Jart Report was busy praying on his downfall, Nooni had been putting together quite the team. If we look back to Week 7, when he had 129.26 points, the core of Stafford, Hendoggy, Carter, Evans, Godwin, Gesicki, and LockettE truly had the potential to compete with anyone. This was a team racing up the roto boards, and we liked them to appear in the semi-finals at worst, if not a trip to the finals. Now, not so much. No shot he makes the playoffs, unless something dramatic happens.

  11. Jason, for a couple weeks I think he was too discouraged to open the app

On To Week Nine!

This Week’s Matchups:

Team ACL Tear vs United Nations: While on paper, one of the top teams facing one the bottom doesn’t seem to provide much intrigue, there is a lot more here than initially meets the eye record wise. JL is certainly struggling to find offensive firepower currently, while MW looks to build off McCaffrey’s return and potentially James Robinson as well. For JL, QB is certainly a question this week, along with the RB2 spot as Merrick Bank’s personal hero and icon Joe Mixon is on bye. Deebo saw much of his dominant role given to Aiyuk and Kittle this last week as well, leaving an 8-1 with a lot more questions than answers. For MW, the big question mark is the WR position. With Darnold slumping - to put it kindly - and Claypool being the 3rd guy at best in Pittsburgh, this team doesn’t have many options at the spot. RB looks good though with potentially four options at least in the short term, and Herbert and Waller are primed for a big day. We just feel more confident taking the team with less question marks this week, and we like MW by 11.7 even in a bounceback week from Ceedee Lamb.

JL: “Always exciting to go against a fellow league champion. MW’s team worries me”

MW: “Too busy to comment”

Real Brothers vs Mike Williams WR1: These teams both suck currently. For Brad, it’s been Mahomes, RB2, and the WRs. For Jart, it’s been RB injuries and the poor play from the big-3 WR corps. There really is not much to say here because there is a lot of talent on the field that currently just isn’t producing. The best we can do is guess at who will perform best, and the proven firepower at least throughout their careers falls on Jart’s side with Tyreek Hill and Davante Adams. D’Andre Swift will certainly be a welcome sight for a hurting Family backfield, and Brandon Aiyuk has a chance to build off of last week with Ja’Marr Chase on bye. Cordarelle-Davante will be the fun matchup of the week given that they were traded for each other. We expect Rodgers to play, and with some nicer performances from the star WRs, we like Real Brothers by 12.2 in a much needed win.

Brad: “Going to absolutely boat race team Jarrett, starting with Baltimore defense getting 15 thurs.”

Jart: “Going to get absolutely boat raced by Brad, starting with Baltimore defense getting 15 thurs.”

GRIDDY GANG vs NN: We’re calling this one the Nooni bowl given how many of these players (especially the stars) have been rostered by Nooni this year. Despite last week’s results, these are two teams that continue to trend in very different directions. The play of Najee and Kupp along with Nooni handing NN every good player he’s ever thought about having has NN riding high, while Jason continues to search for answers from his WRs and an RB2 to replace some of the King’s production. Russell Wilson returns this week, and perhaps that will provide a spark for Jason who won last week but in rather unimpressive fashion. Kamara, Jefferson, and McLaurin all have nice matchups, while Beasley will likely need to get his early in what looks to be a blowout against the Jets. For NN, Najee may score 90 points this week, and Michael Carter seems primed for heavy passing usage, while Kupp should shine on MNF. Diggs similarly will need to get his early on, and Darrel should continue to benefit from CEH’s absence. We could see this one going either way and expect a solid number of points in this one, but given their performances lately, we feel safer taking Noah. We like NN by 16.5.

Jase: “Good win NN”

NN: “Good dub jase”

Team Horses vs Pray for Ridley: The QBs in this matchup are projected to combine to score 52.64 points, which may be the most the Jart Report team has ever seen. Beyond the signal callers, there is still a lot to like about both of these teams, as Aaron Jones has shown he can score, albeit somewhat inconsistently, and Conner should be able to get some carries this week even if Eno is bellcowing. The WRs are certainly a question for Bank, as the team has 5 WR2s who really can give you 15 or 5 depending on how they’re feeling. Some solid matchups this week though gives reason for hope, and Hockenson should have a nice day coming out of the bye. For Folbe, Zeke should bounceback along with the rest of the Cowboys, while Leonard, DK, Jeudy, and Waddle all draw nice matchups. This one feels like it will come down to the matchups, and we love what Folbe has this week. So we like Team Horses by 6.6.

Folbe: “Rumor has it Merrick is still scarred from last years playoff blowout. Hope he comes to play this time around”

Bank: “Idk who I play but they’re in trouble”

Dmichs vs I Got a Half Chubb: The top two scorers from last week face off in what should be a fun one, and is our Jart Report Matchup of the Week. There’s a lot that could be said here, but we expect both teams to perform well. Ultimately, what we see as being the difference maker here is the potential absence of Nick Chubb due to a positive COVID test result. If Chubb can go, we like CJ to win, if he can’t, we like Dmichs. Right now evidence suggests more strongly that he will not be able to, so we like Dmichs by 5.4.

Dmichs: “CJ is losing this week, sorry”

CJ: “I want more wins!”

Aross vs Nooni: Nooni sucks. Like historically so. Not much else to say. Aross by a million.

Aross: “Idek who I play but good win”

Nooni: “We don’t look at the fantasy matchup. Focused on getting the boys ready to rally after a *poop* week”

This week’s award goes to CJ, whose team has clearly rallied around the releasing of their team name, and played their best football to date. Nothing brings the team closer than tragedy.
